(255, 5, 44, 1, 'Irregular Verbs Table', NULL, 'irregular-verbs-table', 'Only a big table; No exercises.', '<p>Simple / Simple Past / Past Participle</p>\r\n<p>awake / awoke / awoken</p>\r\n<p>be / was/were/ been</p>\r\n<p>beat / beat / beaten</p>\r\n<p>become / became / become</p>\r\n<p>begin / began / begun</p>\r\n<p>wake / woke / woken</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-27 21:00:24', '2019-07-27 21:02:23'),
(257, 5, 45, 2, 'The Present Perfect Tense, Part 2', NULL, 'the-present-perfect-tense-2', NULL, '<p>The past participle of all regular verbs is the same as the simple past tense form (add <strong>-ed</strong>).</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INIFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to borrow</td>\r\n<td>borrowed</td>\r\n<td>borrowed</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to cheat</td>\r\n<td>cheated</td>\r\n<td>cheated</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to try</td>\r\n<td>tried</td>\r\n<td>tried</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to offend</td>\r\n<td>offended</td>\r\n<td>offended</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to work</td>\r\n<td>worked</td>\r\n<td>worked</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The part participle of all irregular verbs has a different form and must be studied and learned.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to grow</td>\r\n<td>grew</td>\r\n<td>grown</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to teach</td>\r\n<td>taught</td>\r\n<td>taught</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to be</td>\r\n<td>was/were</td>\r\n<td>been</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to hear</td>\r\n<td>heard</td>\r\n<td>heard</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to take</td>\r\n<td>took</td>\r\n<td>taken</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>It takes a lot of practice to be able to correctly use the present perfect tense.&nbsp; Learn the past participles of all the irregular verbs by heart, and you will quickly be able to use this tense proficiently.</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:01:29', '2019-07-29 03:06:35'),
(258, 5, 45, 3, 'Exercise 1', NULL, 'exercise-1', NULL, '<p>Rewrite the following sentences to create the present perfect tense using has or have and the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; Use the two preceding verb lists to complete this exercise.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercies.</p>\r\n<p>They (to work) in Japan. - have worked</p>\r\n<p>William (to grow) a lot since the last time I saw him. - has grown</p>\r\n<p>I (to hear) that noise in my car several times. - have heard</p>\r\n<p>We (to try) to help them. - have tried</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:06:59', '2019-07-29 03:09:45'),
(259, 5, 45, 4, 'Exercise 2', NULL, 'exercise-2', NULL, '<p>Complete the sentences that follow to create the present perfect tense.&nbsp; Use the contracted pronoun and the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.</p>\r\n<p>Regular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to offer</td>\r\n<td >offered</td>\r\n<td >offered</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to climb</td>\r\n<td >climbed</td>\r\n<td >climbed</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(many more...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Irregular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to forgive</td>\r\n<td >forgave</td>\r\n<td >forgiven</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to bite</td>\r\n<td >bit</td>\r\n<td >biten</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(many more...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>He ___ (to offer) help. - he\'s offered</p>\r\n<p>We ___ (to climb) many mountains. - we\'ve climbed</p>\r\n<p>She ___ (to forgive) you many times. - she\'s forgiven</p>\r\n<p>It ___ (to bite) a few people. - it\'s bitten</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:10:37', '2019-07-29 03:15:44'),
(260, 5, 46, 1, 'The Present Perfect Tense: Negative Form', NULL, 'the-present-perfect-tense--negative-form', NULL, '<p>Place <strong>not</strong> after <strong>has</strong> or <strong>have</strong> to create the negative form of the present perfect tense.&nbsp; Use the past participle of the verb in the negative form.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >I have been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I have not been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I have not been to Paris.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >you have been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >you have not been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >You have not been there.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >he has been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >she has not been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >He has not been nice.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >she has been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >he has not been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >She has not been happy.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >it has been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >it has not been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >It has not been cold.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >we have been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >we have not been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >We have not been busy.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >they have been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >they have not been</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >They have not been on a boat.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:16:17', '2019-07-29 03:19:46'),
(261, 5, 46, 2, 'Part 2: Contactions', NULL, 'part-2--contactions', NULL, '<p>The negative form of the present perfect tense can also be expressed with the contraction <strong>hasn\'t</strong> or <strong>haven\'t</strong>.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >I have not seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I haven\'t seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I haven\'t seen it.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >you have not seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >you haven\'t seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >You haven\'t seen the play.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >he has not seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >he hasn\'t seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >He hasn\'t seen his sister.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >she has not seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >she hasn\'t seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >She hasn\'t seen her brother.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >it has not seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >it hasn\'t seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >It hasn\'t seen me.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >we have not seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >we haven\'t seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >We haven\'t seen the movie.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >they have not seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >they haven\'t seen</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >They haven\'t seen Sara.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:20:04', '2019-07-29 03:23:30'),
(262, 5, 46, 3, 'Part 3: Examples with Regular and Irregular Verbs', NULL, 'part-3--regular-and-irregular-verbs', NULL, '<p>The past participle of all regular verbs is the same as the simple past tense form (add <strong>-ed</strong>).</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to attract</td>\r\n<td>attracted</td>\r\n<td>attracted</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to wait</td>\r\n<td>waited</td>\r\n<td>waited</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to accept</td>\r\n<td>accepted</td>\r\n<td>accepted</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to invent</td>\r\n<td>invented</td>\r\n<td>invented</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The past participle of all irregular verbs has a different form and must be studied and learned.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to find</td>\r\n<td>found</td>\r\n<td>found</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to become</td>\r\n<td>became</td>\r\n<td>become</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to write</td>\r\n<td>wrote</td>\r\n<td>written</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:24:07', '2019-07-29 03:27:49'),
(263, 5, 46, 4, 'Exercise 1', NULL, 'exercise-1', NULL, '<p>Rewrite the following sentences to create the negative form of the present perfect tense.&nbsp; Write your answer once with <strong>has not</strong> and once with <strong>have not</strong> and once with the contraction <strong>hasn\'t</strong> or <strong>haven\'t</strong>.&nbsp; Use the past participle of the verb in parenthese.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.</p>\r\n<p>My teacher (to write) two books. - has not written</p>\r\n<p>My teacher (to write) two books. - hasn\'t written</p>\r\n<p>I (to accept) the offer. - have not accepted</p>\r\n<p>I (to accept) the offer. - haven\'t accepted</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:28:04', '2019-07-29 03:30:56'),
(264, 5, 46, 5, 'Exercise 2', NULL, 'exercise-2', NULL, '<p>Complete the sentences that follow by using the contraction <strong>hasn\'t</strong> or <strong>haven\'t</strong> and the past participle of the verb in parenthesis.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercies.</p>\r\n<h3>Regular</h3>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to solve</td>\r\n<td>solved</td>\r\n<td>solved</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to waste</td>\r\n<td>wasted</td>\r\n<td>wasted</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3>Irregular</h3>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to give</td>\r\n<td>gave</td>\r\n<td>given</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to have</td>\r\n<td>had</td>\r\n<td>had</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>We ___ (to keep) it a secret. - haven\'t kept</p>\r\n<p>You ___ (to give) it a chance. - haven\'t given</p>\r\n<p>You ___ (to waste) my time. - haven\'t wasted</p>\r\n<p>I ___ (to solve) the mystery. - haven\'t solved</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 03:31:11', '2019-07-29 22:36:19'),
(265, 5, 47, 1, 'The Present Perfect Tense: Question Form', NULL, 'the-present-perfect-tense--question-form', NULL, '<p>Place <strong>has</strong> or <strong>have</strong> before the subject to create questions with the present perfect tense.&nbsp; The past participle of the verb is used when forming questions with the present perfect tense.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >I have begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >have I begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >Have I begun to sing better?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >you have begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >have you begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >Have you begun your course?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >he has begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >has he begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >Has he begun to realize it?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >she has begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >has she begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >Has she begun to understand?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >it has begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >has it begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >Has it begun to melt?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >we have begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >have we begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >Have we begun to eat right?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >they have begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >have they begun</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >Have they begun to worry?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The past participle of all regular verbs is the same as the simple past tense form (add <strong>-ed</strong>).</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to apologize</td>\r\n<td >apologized</td>\r\n<td >apologized</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to benefit</td>\r\n<td >benefited</td>\r\n<td >benefited</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(more...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The past participle of all irregular verbs has a different form and must be studied and learned.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to rise</td>\r\n<td >rose</td>\r\n<td >risen</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to hide</td>\r\n<td >hid</td>\r\n<td >hidden</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(more...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 21:40:12', '2019-07-29 21:46:37'),
(266, 5, 47, 2, 'Exercise 1', NULL, 'exercise-1', NULL, '<p>Rewrite the following sentences to create the question form of the present perfect tense by placing <strong>has</strong> or <strong>have</strong> before the subject.&nbsp; Use the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.&nbsp; Don\'t forget to include a question mark (?) in your answer.</p>\r\n<p>You (to show) your report cards to your parents. - Have you shown</p>\r\n<p>The teacher (to correct) all the exams. - Has the teacher corrected</p>\r\n<p>I (to bring) enough for everybody. - Have I brought</p>\r\n<p>My dog (to chew) all the furniture.&nbsp; - Has my dog chewed</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 21:46:54', '2019-07-29 21:49:53'),
(267, 5, 47, 3, 'Exercise 2', NULL, 'exercise-2', NULL, '<p>Rewrite the sentences that follow to create questions in the present perfect tense.&nbsp; Place <strong>has</strong> or <strong>have</strong> before the subject, and use the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.&nbsp; Don\'t forget to include a question mark (?) in your answer.</p>\r\n<p>Regular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INIFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to invest</td>\r\n<td >invested</td>\r\n<td >invested</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to occur</td>\r\n<td >occured</td>\r\n<td >occurred</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Irregular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INIFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to leave</td>\r\n<td >left</td>\r\n<td >left</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to drive</td>\r\n<td >drove</td>\r\n<td >driven</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>You (to iron) the clothes. - Have you ironed the clothes?</p>\r\n<p>He (to drive) many miles. - Has he driven many miles?</p>\r\n<p>It (to occur) a few times. - Has it occurred a few times?</p>\r\n<p>Elvis (to leave) the building. - Has Elvis left the building?</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 21:50:07', '2019-07-29 21:55:02'),
(268, 5, 48, 1, 'The Past Perfect Tense', NULL, 'the-past-perfect-tense', NULL, '<p>The past perfect tense is used to describe a past action that occurred before another past action.&nbsp; For example, one past action occurred at 8:00 P.M, and the previous past action occurred at 7:00 P.M.&nbsp; Use <strong>had</strong> for all persons and the past participle of the verb to create the past perfect tense.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >I have heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I had heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I had heard the news.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >you have heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >you had heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >You had heard the guitar.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >he has heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >he had heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >He had heard you scream.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >she has heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >she had heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >She had heard the song.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >it has heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >it had heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >It had heard the noise.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >we have heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >we had heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >We had heard everything.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >they have heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >they had heard</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >They had heard nothing.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The contraction <strong>\'d</strong> is often used with the pronouns when using the past perfect tense.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >I had learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I\'d learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I\'d learned my lesson.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >you had learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >you\'d learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >You\'d learned how to do it.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >he had learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >he\'d learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >He\'d learned the rules.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >she had learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >she\'d learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >She\'d learned our names.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >it had learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >it\'d learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >It\'d learned how to speak.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >we had learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >we\'d learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >We\'d learned to add.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >they had learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >they\'d learned</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >They\'d learned to spell.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 21:55:38', '2019-07-29 22:02:03'),
(269, 5, 48, 2, 'Part 2', NULL, 'part-2', NULL, '<p>The past participle of all regular verbs is the same as the simple past tense form (add <strong>-ed</strong>).</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to stop</td>\r\n<td >stopped</td>\r\n<td >stopped</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to expect</td>\r\n<td >expected</td>\r\n<td >expected</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to pass</td>\r\n<td >passed</td>\r\n<td >passed</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The past participle of all irregular verbs has a different form and must be studied and learned.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td >SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td >PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to sell</td>\r\n<td >sold</td>\r\n<td >sold</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to see</td>\r\n<td >saw</td>\r\n<td >seen</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >to do</td>\r\n<td >did</td>\r\n<td >done</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td >&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:02:25', '2019-07-29 22:05:35'),
(270, 5, 48, 3, 'Exercise 1', NULL, 'exercise-1', NULL, '<p>Rewrite the following sentences to create the past perfect tense.&nbsp; Use <strong>had</strong> and the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.</p>\r\n<p>We (to decide) to stay home. - had decided to stay home</p>\r\n<p>They (to sell) their boat when they bought the motorcycle. - had sold their boat</p>\r\n<p>I (to have) supper so I only ate the dessert. - had had supper</p>\r\n<p>The rain (to stop) so we went for a walk. - had stopped</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:05:49', '2019-07-29 22:15:07'),
(271, 5, 48, 4, 'Exercise 2', NULL, 'exercise-2', NULL, '<p>Complete the following using <strong>had</strong>&nbsp;and the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.</p>\r\n<p>Regular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to finish</td>\r\n<td>finished</td>\r\n<td>finished</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to order</td>\r\n<td>ordered</td>\r\n<td>ordered</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to rescue</td>\r\n<td>rescued</td>\r\n<td>rescued</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Irregular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to sweep</td>\r\n<td>swept</td>\r\n<td>swept</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to throw</td>\r\n<td>threw</td>\r\n<td>thrown</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to ring</td>\r\n<td>rang</td>\r\n<td>rung</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>She ___ (to throw) it in the garbage. - had thrown it</p>\r\n<p>We ___ (to sing) the song serveral times. - had sung the song</p>\r\n<p>I ___ (to open) the gift when I realized it was for you. - had opened the gift</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:07:07', '2019-07-29 22:12:41'),
(272, 5, 49, 1, 'The Past Perfect Tense: Negative Form', NULL, 'the-past-perfect-tense--negative-form', NULL, '<p>Place <strong>not</strong> after <strong>had</strong> to create the negative form of the past perfect tense.&nbsp; The past participle of the verb is always used in the negative form.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >I had run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I had not run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I had not run after school</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >you had run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >you had not run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >You had not run very far.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >he had run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >he had not run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >He had not run the race.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >she had run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >she had not run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >She had not run with shoes.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >it had run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >it had not run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >It had not run across the road.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >we had run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >we had not run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >We had not run run together.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >they had run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >they had not run</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >They had not run outside.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The negative form of the past perfect tense can also be expressed with the contraction hadn\'t.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >I had not opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I hadn\'t opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >I hadn\'t opened the mail.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >you had not opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >you hadn\'t opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >You hadn\'t opened the book.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >he had not opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >he hadn\'t opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >He hadn\'t opened the letter.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >she had not opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >she hadn\'t opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >She hadn\'t opened her gifts.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >it had not opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >it hadn\'t opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >It hadn\'t opened its mouth.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >we had not opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >we hadn\'t opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >We hadn\'t opened the store.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >they had not opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >they hadn\'t opened</td>\r\n<td >&rarr;</td>\r\n<td >They hadn\'t opened&nbsp;it.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:18:18', '2019-07-29 22:24:05'),
(273, 5, 49, 2, 'Part 2', NULL, 'part-2', NULL, '<p>The past participle of all regular verbs is the same as the simple past tense form (add <strong>-ed</strong>).</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to notice</td>\r\n<td>noticed</td>\r\n<td>noticed</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to follow</td>\r\n<td>followed</td>\r\n<td>followed</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to arrive</td>\r\n<td>arrived</td>\r\n<td>arrived</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The past participle of all irregular verbs has a different form and must be studied and learned.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to fly</td>\r\n<td>flew</td>\r\n<td>flown</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to see</td>\r\n<td>saw</td>\r\n<td>seen</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to hold</td>\r\n<td>held</td>\r\n<td>held</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:24:33', '2019-07-29 22:27:47'),
(274, 5, 49, 3, 'Exercise 1', NULL, 'exercise-1', NULL, '<p>Rewrite the following sentences to create the negative form of the past perfect tense.&nbsp; Write your answer once with <strong>had not</strong>&nbsp;and once with the contraction <strong>hadn\'t</strong>.&nbsp; Use the past participle of the verb in parenthese.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.</p>\r\n<p>He (to hold) a baby before today. - had not held a baby</p>\r\n<p>He (to hold) a baby before today. - hadn\'t held a baby</p>\r\n<p>I (to notice) that you were standing there. - had not noticed that you were standing there</p>\r\n<p>I (to notice) that you were standing there. - hadn\'t noticed that you were standing there</p>\r\n<p>We (to fly) before, so we were nervous. - had not flown before so we were nervous.</p>\r\n<p>We (to fly) before, so we were nervous. - hadn\'t flown before so we were nervous.</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:28:13', '2019-07-29 22:30:55'),
(275, 5, 49, 4, 'Exercise 2', NULL, 'exercise-2', NULL, '<p>Complete the sentences that follow by using the contraction <strong>hadn\'t</strong> and the past participle of the verb in parenthesis.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercies.</p>\r\n<p>Regular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to rain</td>\r\n<td>rained</td>\r\n<td>rained</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to smoke</td>\r\n<td>smoked</td>\r\n<td>smoked</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Irregular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to eat</td>\r\n<td>ate</td>\r\n<td>eaten</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to give</td>\r\n<td>gave</td>\r\n<td>given</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>We ___ (to eat) our breakfast so we were hungry. - we hadn\'t eaten our breakfast</p>\r\n<p>You ___ (to talk) about that before today. - hadn\'t talked about that before today</p>\r\n<p>I ___ (to buy) butter so I went back to the store again. - hadn\'t bought butter so I went back to the store again</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:31:13', '2019-07-29 22:35:48'),
(276, 5, 50, 1, 'The Past Perfect Tense: Question Form', NULL, 'the-past-perfect-tense--question-form', NULL, '<p>Place <strong>had</strong> before the subject to create the question form of the past perfect tense.&nbsp; The past participle of the verb is used when forming questions in the past perfect tense.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>I had worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>had I worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>Had I worked with you?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>you had worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>had you worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>Had you worked in Mexico?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>he had worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>had he worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>Had he worked for his father?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>she had worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>had she worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>Had she worked in the city?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>it had worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>had it worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>Had it worked well?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>we had worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>had we worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>Had we worked together?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>they had worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>had they worked</td>\r\n<td>&rarr;</td>\r\n<td>Had they worked late?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The past participle of all regular verbs is the same as the simple past tense form (add <strong>-ed</strong>).</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to plan</td>\r\n<td>planned</td>\r\n<td>planned</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to live</td>\r\n<td>lived</td>\r\n<td>lived</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The past participle of all irregular verbs has a different form and must be studied and learned.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to withdraw</td>\r\n<td>withdrew</td>\r\n<td>withdrawn</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to know</td>\r\n<td>knew</td>\r\n<td>known</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:41:30', '2019-07-29 22:47:47'),
(277, 5, 50, 2, 'Exercise 1', NULL, 'exercise-1', NULL, '<p><span >Rewrite the following sentences to create the question form of the past perfect tense by placing </span><span >had</span><span >&nbsp;before the subject.&nbsp; Use the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.&nbsp; Don\'t forget to include a question mark (?) in your answer.</span></p>\r\n<p><span >He (to know) that you were my brother. - Had he known that your were my brother?</span></p>\r\n<p><span >They&nbsp;</span><span >(to withdraw) all the money. - Had withdrawn all the money?</span></p>\r\n<p><span >You&nbsp;</span><span >(to give) him your phone number. - Had you given him your phone number?</span></p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:48:05', '2019-07-29 22:50:27'),
(278, 5, 50, 3, 'Exercise 2', NULL, 'exercise-2', NULL, '<p>Rewrite the sentences that follow to create questions in the past perfect tense.&nbsp; Place <strong>had</strong> before the subject, and use the past participle of the verb in parentheses.&nbsp; You have already learned these verbs in previous exercises.&nbsp; Don\'t forget to include a question mark (?) in your answer.</p>\r\n<p>Regular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INIFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to realize</td>\r\n<td>realized</td>\r\n<td>realized</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to play</td>\r\n<td>played</td>\r\n<td>played</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Irregular</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>INIFINITIVE</td>\r\n<td>SIMPLE PAST</td>\r\n<td>PAST PARTICIPLE</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to take</td>\r\n<td>took</td>\r\n<td>taken</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>to be</td>\r\n<td>was/were</td>\r\n<td>been</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(more verbs...)</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>You (to realize) what she did. - Had you realized what she did?</p>\r\n<p>He (to take) the wrong bus. - Had he taken the wrong bus?</p>\r\n<p>It (to seem) fair to everyone. - Had it seemed fair to everyone?</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-29 22:50:45', '2019-07-29 22:54:14'),
(279, 2, 1, 5, 'Vocabulario Nuevo 4 - Converted', NULL, 'vocabulario-nuevo-4', NULL, '<p>Que se hace o se dice de una manera demasiado r&aacute;pida o con excesiva prisa. - precipitado</p>\r\n<p>rush, dar prisa a, llegar r&aacute;pido - precipitarse</p>\r\n<p>gran pendiente o inclinaci&oacute;n casi vertical - acantilado</p>\r\n<p>gato - cucho</p>\r\n<p>shabby - desgastado</p>\r\n<p>knack, habilidad, destreza, maestr&iacute;a, arte - ma&ntilde;a</p>\r\n<p>disponer algo con ma&ntilde;a para falsearlo y obtener un provecho. - ama&ntilde;ar</p>\r\n<p>trabajo realizado con las manos, en especial&nbsp; en escolares como ejercicio de desarrollo creativo; artesan&iacute;a; craft - manualidad</p>\r\n<p>causar una fuerte impresi&oacute;n; dazzle - deslumbrar</p>\r\n<p>que deslumbra; luz ___ - cegador/a</p>\r\n<p>sentimiento en el &aacute;nimo producidos por algo que no se desea o espera. - disgusto</p>\r\n<p>hacer enojar o disgustar profundamente a alguien - encabronar</p>\r\n<p>convertirse en polvo, decaer, desmigar - desmoronar</p>\r\n<p>incorrecto, impropio, indecoroso, deshonesto - indebido</p>\r\n<p>separar algo o dividir un todo en partes para estudiarlas - desglosar</p>\r\n<p>romper, descomponer, desglosar, analizar - estropearse</p>\r\n<p>vicioso, hosco, malhumorado, surly&nbsp; - arisco</p>\r\n<p>d&eacute;bil, ligero, p&aacute;lido, vago - tenue</p>\r\n<p>ignorar, overlook - pasar por alto</p>\r\n<p>hustle and bustle - ajetreo y bullicio</p>\r\n<p>axila - sobaco</p>\r\n<p>arabe de africa del norte - magreb</p>\r\n<p>intimidar - amedrentar</p>\r\n<p>nublado, nuboso - turbio</p>\r\n<p>lobbiest - cabildero</p>\r\n<p>cosa que permite deducir la existencia de algo; pista - indicio</p>\r\n<p>esencial, fundamental - imprescindible</p>\r\n<p>que va contra la raz&oacute;n, la prudencia o la sensatez; salvaje - descabellado</p>\r\n<p>que es extraordinariamente malo o no puede ser peor - p&eacute;simo</p>', 1, 42, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-30 18:53:41', '2020-04-30 05:08:34'),
(280, 1, 2, 1, 'Verbs', NULL, 'verbs', NULL, '<p>Verbs are action words.</p>\r\n<p>Verbs are formed according to the subject and the time.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The time: past, present, or future</li>\r\n<li>The subject: I, you, he, she, it, we, or they.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Here are some examples using the verb <strong>To Work</strong>.</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-borderless\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Present</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>I&nbsp;work</strong>&nbsp;every day.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Past</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>I&nbsp;worked</strong>&nbsp;yesterday.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Future</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>I will&nbsp;work</strong>&nbsp;next week.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Present</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>He works</strong>&nbsp;on a farm.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Past</strong></td>\r\n<td>Last year,&nbsp;<strong>he worked</strong>&nbsp;in the city.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Future</strong></td>\r\n<td>Next week,&nbsp;<strong>he will work</strong>&nbsp;at night.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-07-31 08:22:29', '2019-07-31 19:29:54'),
(310, 11, 1, 2, 'New Vocabulary 1', NULL, 'vocabulary-list-1', 'The personal pronouns.', '<p>From this point on, we will use the personal pronouns to learn how to use verb tenses.</p>\r\n<div class=\"lesson-examples\">\r\n<p><strong>I</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>you</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>he</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>she</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>it</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>we</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>they</strong></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>Please look up the personal pronouns and other words in your native language and add them to your vocabulary list.</p>', 1, 20, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2019-08-10 08:04:13', '2019-08-17 03:29:24'),
